import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

def round_to_integer(val):
	# return round(val, 0)
	if (np.isnan(val)):
		return np.nan
	if (val == 0):
		return val
	return np.floor(val)

A was a boy, B, a girl, C, a girl, D, a boy, and E and F married couple.  A sleepwalked out of the camp in the night and got lost and injured. In the morning he woke up and came back to the camp. They immediately organized emergency team and asked someone to go searching for A.  When E found A, both of them were still asleep.  The others got separated during the searching so that C and D went back to the camp to collect additional emergency gear after finishing their search, and A was found by F. C asked A how he got lost, but A ignored her, so C continued to search the whole day, but did not find him.  On the other hand B and E had to return to the camp to look for C and D in order to have dinner, but they found out that none of the others had returned.  After they finished looking for C and D they both returned to the tents. D asked C if he found A during his search, but C replied that she did not.  B slept well enough without taking any painkillers he had, but E couldn't sleep well due to the pain, so E slept less than B.  During the next day C stayed at the camp where the others had a great time swimming and enjoying the sun.  Towards the end of the day they found A who was unconscious but not injured.  When A woke up they were almost ready to head back home and so on the way they stopped at a bar for D to check her email, and bought some snacks for B and C and other camp supplies for A. When they got back home they realized that A must have come home alone from the camp and they thought it was much more fun if there were only 6 of them.

#### Solution:
I used python but many languages can solve this and I've left the source up so anyone can run it on their machine. 
I ran this locally by downloading the file and I've also made it available as a codepen you can follow below (it's also a live pen so you can see as I work through problems if you're on the live screen of devpost)..

https://codepen.io/andylewis/live/QbQyR

The above code will run in python. It consists of 5 functions and each function can be submitted as an answer. The code uses a text editor to accept an answer with each input. 
I also added some additional logging to print messages back to the main program to keep track of where you are in the algorithm.

This was my first solution and I think it's good since it's pretty solid and uses a really cool idea. 
This project makes for a great beginner project but doesn't take a lot of advanced python skills to complete. 
This was a very long process and I think the longest project I've ever worked on on devpost but it was also very rewarding so I recommend this as a first project. 
I'd also like to say thank you so much for participating in this competition. I loved the idea of people coming up with answers to my questions, which is why I used a text editor as opposed to some kind of automated system.

```python
def isPrime(num):
    if num < 1:
        return False
    for i in range(2, int(num**0.5)+1):
        if num%i == 0:
            return False
    return True
def printPrimes(limit = 20):
    primeList = []
    for i in xrange(1, limit+1):
        if isPrime(i):
            primeList.append(i)

    print primeList
printPrimes()
```

```
# Solution
Tips for multiple choice:
If the answer is in terms of a variable, then the variable is in the equation.
An equation contains 1 unknown that needs to be replaced, otherwise no variables are used in the equation.
Once you figure out something by putting the variable in the equation, then you can figure out the entire solution by using substitution instead.
Substitution for this problem is to put n-1. If it is a 2n+1, then 1-1=0 which is just n.

n=(3n+1+4n-5)+(n-5)=2n+1+5-5=n (using the n=n)

We don't have n^2 here so 3a+n+1+3n+4n-5+2n-1+9=0.

Let's substitute the variables into the equation to see what happens:

3a+n+2n-1=0 (Using the variables as 3a=n and 3a+n-1=0)

This means that:
3a=n-1 (Using 3a=n)
3a (since 3a=n-one)
= n-1 (since a is a number)
Then we'll have 2n+3n-3=1

Then n=1

n=2n+3n=3

Then the number of Schnuzzers=3
```

<details><summary>Cracking the Code 1</summary>

Three years ago, there were 287 students in Mr. Boss’ 8th grade English class, and four years ago, there were twice as many students in the 7th grade as the 8th grade, and two years ago, there were three times as many students in the English class as in the US history class. If there are 380 students in the English and history classes combined, how many 7th graders are in the 8th grade English history class?

<div markdown = "1">***
**Solution:**
You can solve this by using recursive logic:

First off assume the number of students in the 7 th grade is N;
then the students in gr 8th is 3 times of N.

Since the total number of students in 7th and 8th is 860;
then there should be 3 860/3 = 287 students of grade 8th 
and gr 8th should have 60 times of students of gr 7th, which equals 1129 students. 
Then subtract the number of students in 8th grade from the number of students in all grades, 
1129 - 287 = 842 students in all the classes.
Finally, this is a trick; if there's one person in all the classes other than a teacher, than there's only one student; 
so to find the number of 7th standard students is to divide,842-1, with N to get the number of students

```python
def solution(n: int, m: int, k: int):

    # 0 <= n <= m <= 10000, 0 <= k <= m

    # Solution is 97
    if n + m == k:
        return True

    if ((n//m)*(m//m)-(n//n-1)*(n//n-2)*(m//m-1)*(m//m)) <= k <= ((n//m)*n+(m//m)*(m-1)/(m-2)) * (m//m-1) - (n//n-1) <= 1:
        return True    

    return False
```

class Solution:
  def solve(self, s, a2, a1, a0):
    # the sum of all the values from the inputs
    sum = 0
    # the total length of all the numbers in the input
    length = 0
    
    for i in range(len(s)):
      # sum the values for the first part of the input
      sum += int(s[i])
      
      # add lengths to the sum
      sum += length
      
      # increment the position in the string
      length += 1

    # return the difference between the sum and the values in the second part of the input
    return sum - a1 + a2
  
  def solution(self, x):
    return sum([self.solve(s, a2, a, x) for x in range(0, 3) for a3, a2, a in zip(x-1, x, x+1)])

def bracketChars(s):
  """
  s is a string, it can be any string, it is expected to have 1-3 sets of 
  brackets in it
  """
    brackets = []  # Initialize brackets list
    # Traverse s and store each brackets encountered, also check if
    # it is not already in brackets
    for index, letter in enumerate(s):
        if letter == '[' or letter == '(':
            brackets.append(letter)
            # If brackets have been found, check if they are already in brackets list
            if (bracketChars(s[:index]) in brackets):
                # If brackets have been previously been found, break and continue
                break
        elif letter == ']' or letter == ')':
            # If brackets are encountered at end of string, print
            # them with all other brackets encountered
            if (brackets in brackets):
                break
                # If brackets are not on first 3 elements, print them
            else:
                brackets.append(letter),
# Your outputs should be an array (brackets + string between brackets)
    if brackets:
        return brackets + s[:len(brackets)]
    else:
        return s + brackets

class Solution:
    def solution(self,n):
        def recursive(n):
            if (n==1):
                return 1
            else:
                if (n%2==0):
                    return n/2+recursive(n/2)
                else:
                    return sum(recursive(i)*i for i in range(n/2,n,-1))+n/2
                    return 0

     
        return recursive(n)

```
	The 'if...then' statements in programming languages allow programming statements to conditionally execute if a defined condition is true.  This condition is called the test. You must have a way to check a value for true, otherwise you might as well hard coded the value in.

- Please include all of the operators and how they work.

		+: concatenate / add 
		-: subtract / subract 
		*: multiply 
		/: divide 
		^: exponentiantation 
		%: modulus (floored) (I use this a lot for calculating 24 hour times with decimal minutes since it is more accurate.  For example (3:30 mod 1 = 0, 3:30 mod.5 = 0.5)
		&: and  
		|: or  
		!: not  

	The above have a few special cases.

		x: multiplication and addition (x & 3 = any nonzero number of digits on the left)
		&^: shift (x & 3 is 0 for nonzero values and 0 is x & x which is zero)
		==: comparing two values for equality (not equals or!= is == without the "=")
		<>: comparing two values for difference with a value (0 for == and!= is the value that is NOT in the comparison)
		<>=": comparing two strings for difference with case (like spaces and special characters)
		<: comparing to a smaller int. (<= is the opposite of what you want)
```
